Here’s to moments of self-care, glowing skin, and the beautiful connection that motherhood brings.  This Mother’s Day, don’t forget to treat your mum or special someone to a little extra love and self-care with our special gifts and our luxurious treatments in salon.

Your Mother’s Day Luxe Gift is waiting... 
Today’s the final day to redeem your glow-worthy bundle:

No matter how full life gets, every person deserves to feel radiant in their own skin. 

Gift the glow with a luxurious skin experience, for mum, yourself or someone special. 

Discover our Mother’s Day treatments in salon today.

This month, it’s all about self-care and the right skincare! Everyone deserves a little luxury in their routine.

You deserve a skincare routine as radiant as you are! Here are a few easy tips to keep your skin glowing all day long:
1.Hydrate, hydrate, hydrate:  Start with a refreshing mist to lock in moisture.
2.	Don���t skip SPF:  Protect your skin from those harmful rays all year round.

Mother’s Day is fast approaching, and we have the perfect skincare duo to keep them glowing day and night!

Start her morning with the Eternal Replenishing Day Cream — a luxurious moisturizer that hydrates, protects, and supports a radiant, smooth complexion all day long. 

Then, let her unwind with the Eternal Regenerating Night Cream, designed to deeply nourish and restore while she sleeps, so she wakes up to softer, more rejuvenated skin.

Because your special someone deserves to feel their best, no matter the time of day.

Mum’s skincare, simplified! Whether she’s always on-the-go or loves a little moment of luxury, a refreshing face mist is the perfect pick-me-up.

Daily Hydration Mist for soothing, all-day hydration

It was a pleasure to host incredible partners like Eric Hamberger, Managing Director at @whartonschool, whose insights and presence made the summit even more impactful. 

From forging new relationships to reconnecting with old ones, the summit brought the global education community together in meaningful ways. 

Check out Eric’s insights from this incredible event!

#Emeritus #ASUGSVEmeritusSummit #EducationInnovation #AllEyesOnIndia #TheWhartonSchool

Natasha Banth, Senior Vice President - University Relationships at Emeritus, came to the ASU+GSV & Emeritus Summit with high expectations. The event not only met them, it exceeded them.

We’ve already started counting down to 2026 🥳

#Emeritus #ASUGSVEmeritusSummit #Edtech #FutureOfLearning

From expanding global access to education across PreK - Gray sectors to sparking conversations that will shape the future, the impact of the ASU+GSV & Emeritus Summit has been nothing short of extraordinary in the last three years. 

Emeritus founder Chaitanya Kalipatnapu drops in to talk about the summit and issues a subtle reminder that #LearningAtTheSpeedOfLight isn't just a theme for this year's summit; it is more of a call to action for the rest of the year. 

#ASUGSVEmeritusSummit #AllEyesOnIndia #Edtech

We caught up with Avnish Singhal, Executive Vice President - India & APAC, Emeritus, at the 3rd ASU+GSV & Emeritus Summit. He shared his key takeaways from the summit and the role of innovation in ensuring accessible and affordable education. 

#AllEyesOnIndia #EducationInnovation #Emeritus #ASUGSVEmeritusSummit #EmeritusIndia

How would you describe one of India’s best and biggest Edtech events? Leave a comment!

Up next: A conversation on Edtech unicorns, sustainable models, and IPO success! 
 
Emeritus CFO Pranjal Kumar will break down what it takes for Indian #EdTech to scale, sustain, and go public with Nikhil Barshikar, Mukul Rustagi and Sajith Pai for company. 

Will IPOs be the next big chapter in India’s booming edtech story?

Let’s dive in to find out on Day 3 of the ASU+GSV & Emeritus Summit 2025. 
 
#ASUGSVEmeritusSummit #AllEyesOnIndia #Edtech @asugsvsummit

Education isn’t about ranking students—it’s about empowering them.

In conversation with Chaitanya Kalipatnapu at the ASU+GSV & Emeritus Summit, Neeru Khosla emphasized the need for a more inclusive, confidence-building approach to learning. The goal isn’t for everyone to be an ‘A’—it’s to ensure no one is left behind.

Catch more some thought-provoking conversations on Day 3 of the Summit!

#ASUGSVEmeritusSummit #AllEyesOnIndia #Edtech @ASUGSVSummit

As we wrap up an unforgettable summit, Day 3 brings you the final round of impactful sessions and visionary insights. From groundbreaking innovations to thought-provoking discussions, today is the day to witness the future of education unfold.

#Emeritus #AllEyesOnIndia #ASUGSVEmeritusSummit #EdTech @asugsvsummit

Ankit Aggarwal from @unstop.world is here at @asugsvsummit 🤩 are you here too? Leave a comment and let us know!

It has been an exciting and eventful day at the ASU+GSV & Emeritus Summit 2025 🥳 Are you ready for DAY THREE?

#ASUGSVEmeritusSummit #FutureOfLearning #AI #EdTech #Leadership @emeritus_ed

Emeritus’ Ganesh S sums up what was an eye-opening day of learning and insights on Day 2 of the ASU+GSV & Emeritus Summit. 

He looks back on some of the discussions that took place - from the story of Swiggy’s IPO journey with CFO Rahul Bothra and Ashwin Damera to Chaitanya Kalipatnapu’s conversation with Suresh Prabhu.

And he’s looking forward to a solid Day 3 line-up featuring hashtag#MaryKom, Viren Rasquinha and Ronnie Screwvala.

#ASUGSVEmeritusSummit #AllEyesOnIndia #Edtech @asugsvsummit

The Little church on the Hill
On a hilltop, nestled among the trees, stands a little wooden church.
It is a simple church, but it is filled with love and faith. The doors
are always open, and the people of the town are always welcome
inside.
The litle church on the hill is a place where people come to pray, to
sing, and to celebrate. It is a place where they can find comfort and
strength. It is a place where they can come together as a community.
The little church on the hill is a symbol of hope and peace. It is a
reminder that there is always good in the world, and that even in the
darkest of times, there is always light.

Excited to finally share our latest initiative over at @officialblackwallstreet! Over the past 10 years (🤯), one of the biggest lessons I’ve learned is the priceless value of community. My sanity has been kept intact thanks to the Black founders in my circle who remind me that I’m not alone in this journey. We’re all facing similar challenges, and we can navigate them more effectively together.

Issa Rae once said it best, “We have a tendency to try to network up, but it’s really about networking across. Who’s next to you? Who’s struggling? Who’s in the trenches with you? Build with them.” There’s so much power in building with our peers.

This is why I’m so proud to introduce the OBWS Founders Club—a community for ambitious Black entrepreneurs (& aspiring founders) to intentionally connect, share resources, support, and uplift each other. 🙌🏾

If you’re a Black founder or aspiring founder looking for a supportive network, real connections, and access to resources, this is for you. Learn more and apply through the link in my bio or at founders.obws.com 

Anddd if you’d like to partner on events, workshops, provide resources, or anything in between, hit me up!

On May 1st 1950, Gwendolyn Brooks made history as the first African American to win a Pulitzer Prize, receiving the honor for her poetry collection Annie Allen, a coming-of-age portrait of a young Black girl navigating love, war, and womanhood.⁠
⁠
Born in Topeka, Kansas, and raised in Chicago, Brooks began writing at a young age and published her first poem at just 13.  Her work wasn’t just poetry, it was protest, pride, and power. From We Real Cool to The Bean Eaters, Brooks told stories that mattered, in a voice that couldn’t be ignored.⁠
⁠
She later became the Poet Laureate of Illinois and the Library of Congress’ Consultant in Poetry, blazing a trail for Black writers across the nation.⁠
⁠
👑 A literary icon.⁠

On April 19, 1978, Max Robinson made history as the first Black anchor of a network newscast, joining ABC World News Tonight in 1978 and breaking barriers in American journalism.⁠
⁠
Born in Richmond, Virginia, in 1939, Robinson faced systemic racism early in life, including being expelled from college for staging a protest against segregation. Still, he pushed forward, studying at Virginia Union University, an HBCU, and later launching his broadcasting career at a local TV station where his image was initially hidden behind a screen to conceal his race.⁠
⁠
But Robinson refused to be silenced or sidelined.⁠
⁠
He rose to national prominence not just for his commanding presence and journalistic excellence, but for using his platform to speak truth to power and advocate for more honest representation of Black communities in media. 👏🏾⁠
⁠

52 years ago today, this Black woman made history and paved the way for generations of leaders to come. 🗳️⁠
⁠
In 1973, Lelia Foley was elected mayor of Taft, Oklahoma, becoming the first Black woman elected mayor in the United States. A divorced mother of five living on welfare, Lelia Foley didn’t wait for change, she decided to become the change. ⁠

After being inspired by a visit to her community from civil rights leader Shirley Chisholm, Foley raised just $200, ran for office, and won. Let her story remind you: no background or barrier is too big when purpose and power align. 👏🏾⁠

On this day 57 years ago, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. delivered his final, prophetic speech: 'I've Been to the Mountaintop.' ✊🏾🔥"⁠
⁠
Standing before a crowd in Memphis on April 3, 1968, Dr. King spoke with an urgency that still resonates today. He reflected on the struggles of the Civil Rights Movement, the fight for economic justice, and the promise of a better future. His words on economic power and collective action still resonate today.⁠
⁠
💬 “We've got to strengthen Black institutions. I call upon you to take your money out of the banks downtown and deposit your money in Tri-State Bank—we want a ‘bank-in’ movement in Memphis.”⁠
⁠
Dr. King understood that economic empowerment was key to liberation. He urged Black communities to invest in their own financial institutions, boycott businesses that exploited Black workers, and build collective economic strength. His message is a reminder that where we spend and invest our money is a powerful tool for change.⁠
⁠
Less than 24 hours later, he was assassinated, but his words and mission live on. Dr. King's vision for justice, equality, and economic empowerment remains as powerful and necessary as ever. #BlackExcellence

On this day 61 years ago, Malcolm X delivered his iconic 'Ballot or the Bullet' speech in Cleveland, Ohio, on April 3, 1964. 🔥 His message was clear: Black Americans must use their political power strategically and demand their civil rights.⁠
⁠
🗳️ 'The time has come for Black people to fight back in self-defense whenever and wherever they are unjustly and unlawfully attacked.'⁠
⁠
💡 He challenged systemic oppression and called for unity beyond religious or ideological differences, stating:⁠
"Whether you are a Christian or a Muslim or a nationalist, we all have the same problem. They don’t hang you because you're a Baptist; they hang you because you’re Black!"⁠
⁠
📢 Malcolm X urged the Black community to use the ballot wisely. Demand real change from politicians or refuse to support those who don’t serve Black interests. His message remains as relevant today as it was in 1964.⁠
⁠
✊🏾 Do you think his words still apply today? Drop your thoughts in the comments! 👇🏾⁠

41 years ago today, Coach John Thompson 🕊️ became the FIRST Black head coach to win an NCAA basketball championship! Leading Georgetown University to victory in 1984, Thompson not only secured a historic title but also paved the way for future Black coaches in college basketball.⁠
⁠
Born and raised in Washington, D.C., Thompson was a dominant force on the court before stepping into coaching. A 6’10” center, he played college ball at Providence College, where he led the team to the NIT Championship in 1963 and became an All-American. After a brief stint in the NBA with the Boston Celtics—winning two championships as a backup to Bill Russell—he transitioned to coaching, taking over Georgetown’s basketball program in 1972.⁠
⁠
Thompson transformed the Hoyas into a powerhouse, mentoring future NBA legends like Patrick Ewing, Alonzo Mourning, and Allen Iverson. Off the court, he was a fierce advocate for Black student-athletes, famously walking out on an NCAA meeting in protest of rules that he felt unfairly targeted underprivileged players. 👏🏾 #BlackExcellence #BlackHistory⁠
⁠
May he continue to rest in power. 🕊️

On this day in 1965, the historic Selma to Montgomery March culminated as thousands of demonstrators arrived at the Alabama State Capitol, marking a pivotal moment in the fight for voting rights. ⁠
⁠
Led by Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., the marchers embarked on a five-day, 54-mile journey. Under federal protection, they covered about 12 miles a day and slept in fields and makeshift camps along U.S. Route 80, enduring physical exhaustion and threats to demand equal voting rights for African Americans.⁠
⁠
The march followed earlier attempts that were met with violent opposition, notably the events of "Bloody Sunday" on March 7, 1965, when peaceful protesters were brutally attacked at the Edmund Pettus Bridge. Despite these challenges, the marchers persevered, and their efforts contributed significantly to the passage of the Voting Rights Act of 1965, a landmark achievement in the Civil Rights Movement. ✊🏾 #BlackHistory⁠
⁠

Thanks to @chobani and @omsom, I made a delicious Burger out of a mashup of my two favorite flavors: Korean and Greek! I’ve been loving tzatziki sauce on my toasts last year, and I thought it would go so well in a burger with a Korean twist. Enjoy a juicy Korean Bulgogi burger with a creamy, refreshing, crunchy sauce.   🍔 Ingredients 🍔 • 1 cup of Chobani® Plain Whole Milk Greek Yogurt
• 1 cup of shredded cucumbers
• Handful of fresh dill
• Pinch of salt 
• Ground black pepper
• 1 tbsp olive oil 
• 1 toast
• 1/2 packet of Omsom Spicy Bulgogi Sauce 
• 150g (⅔ cup) ground beef
• 1/3 tsp baking powder
• Potato burger buns
• Lettuce
• Tomato 

🍴 Directions 🍴 1. Mix the ground beef with salt, pepper, and baking powder. Set aside.
2. Shred the cucumbers and mix with ½ tsp of kosher salt. Set aside for 5 minutes. 
3. Chop the dill into small pieces.
4. Place the shredded cucumbers in a paper towel and squeeze out the excess water.
5. In a bowl, mix the Greek Yogurt, cucumbers, dill, salt, and olive oil.
6. Shape and press the ground beef into a patty, and cook both sides on a heated oiled pan for 2 minutes on each side, or until browned.
7. Lower the heat to the lowest setting. Add ½ packet of Omsom Spicy Bulgogi sauce on top of the beef patty, and flip the patty several times while the sauce bubbles and glazes over the patty. For a well-done burger, lower the heat and put a lid on top of the pan for the meat to finish cooking.
8. On toasted buns, stack the spicy bulgogi patty, spread some tzatziki sauce, add tomato slices and some lettuce. Enjoy!

Chef’s Tip: For extra flavor, add a teaspoon of minced garlic to the tzatziki sauce before serving.

I had walked life’s path with an easy tread
Had followed where comfort and pleasure led;
And then one day in a quiet place
I met the Master, face to face.

With station and rank and wealth for a goal
Much thought for the body, but none for the soul;
I had thought to win in life’s mad race,
When I met the Master, face to face.

I had built my castles and reared them high,
Till their towers pierced the blue of the sky,
I had vowed to rule with an iron mace,
When I met the Master, face to face.

I met Him and knew Him, and blushed to see
That eyes full of sorrow were turned on me;
And I faltered, and fell at His feet that day,
While all my castles melted away.

Melted and vanished, and in their place
I saw nought else but my Master’s face;
And I cried aloud: “Oh, make me meet
To follow the path of Thy wounded feet.”

And now my thoughts are for the souls of men,
I’ve lost my life, to find it again.
E’er since that day in a quiet place
I met the Master, face to face.

#happymothersday #giftofmotherhood

I never realized the importance of community until a few years ago.

For me, the beginning years of my legal career left me feeling like I was very much on an island.

I don’t mean to say that I didn’t have support. I have been very lucky to have incredible, incredible friends, a supportive family and the best boyfriend and then husband anyone could ask for, BUT I didn’t have a group where I could openly share my struggles, discuss ways to improve my career, life and business and collaborate with others in a way that felt genuine, empowering and exciting.

And I think a part of me felt like I needed to earn it on my own, to experience and work through the struggle by myself in order to be truly “successful.” Total hogwash.

Community just hits different. And let’s face it, sometimes our loved ones don’t always want to hear about or even understand what we go through in certain phases of our life, whether it’s starting law school, building a business or even becoming a new mom. That is where community comes in.

Since I left Biglaw and went off on my own to start @flourishlawgroup and continue to build @wealthylawyersquad , I discovered the true power of community.

The conversations. The inspiration. And the support to keep going when it feels hard and you feel alone.
One of my favorite communities that I have joined is The Daily Drip.

I am forever grateful to this community for the support they provide to me as a modern South Florida businesswoman.

And, if you tell me there is a photoshoot involved, you better believe I’ll be there! 

Where are you finding your sense of community? I would love to know!

#southfloridabusinesswoman #community #womeninbusiness #womenowned

I am the co-founder of Flourish Law Group, a boutique law firm specializing in trusts and estates, probate and trust administration, and elder law. We are also adding real estate closings and title work as an additional practice area very soon. With over 20 years of experience in tax and trusts and estates, my law partner and I take a hands-on and personalized approach to planning for our clients. We have seen what happens when a person does not have effective estate planning in place and, as a result, our goal is to educate the community and provide top-notch services to make sure families protect their legacies. Our motto is that “we help families flourish at all stages of life.” I am also the founder of The Wealthy Lawyer $quad, a community for law students and new lawyers, which provides programming, education and coaching for the law school process and the first years as an attorney, and focuses on developing confidence, healthy mindset, and strong mental wellbeing and creating a dream career and wealth. In the $quad, we have one coaching program specifically curated for law students called The Law School Success Blueprint and we are launching a separate coaching program curated for new lawyers called The Lawyer Success Blueprint. I am also the host of The Wealthy Lawyer $quad Podcast, where our mission is to provide content that inspires, empowers and supports law students and new lawyers who want to dream big and I strive to shake up the status quo of what it means to be a successful lawyer in today’s world. I’m also a wife, mom, and real estate investor and love to read, workout, travel, try new foods and talk about business and entrepreneurship.

A Will GUARANTEES your family will be going to court for probate ⚖️

I spent yesterday morning at the annual Probate and Guardianship Conference at the new courthouse.

Probate is when someone passes away and the court decides what happens to what they’ve left behind.

While Guardianship is when someone is deemed to be unable to make their own decisions and the court appoints a guardian — this involves minors and those with memory loss issues like dementia.

So many people think that if you have a will, that’s enough. A will GUARANTEES that you will go through probate — all of which becomes public record and can involve a lot more taxes.

There were judges at the conference from Broward, Miami-Dade and Palm Beach counties.

In Broward, the probate division is seeing a 40% increase in filings year-over-year while there hasn’t been a budget for a new probate judge since 2000-2002.

The judges GENUINELY care about doing a great job and want this process to be better but they are COMPLETELY overloaded.

That’s just another reason to avoid ever having to go through probate.

The conversations at the conference heavily focused around the transfer of property because SO MANY probates (last stats I’ve seen say 70%) probates involve property.

Legacies aren’t built when everything is good — it’s built in how the lows are prepared for.

If you want to learn more about how to protect your legacy, we interview experts and attorneys like @lawyerlaurenklein on our Legacy Show to help you handle these exact situations.

Back at the NXT Conclave 2025, I had the honour of joining 20 visionary global leaders to speak on something deeply close to my heart, emotional and mental well-being. 🇮🇳

It felt historic to represent India with tools that aren’t new or foreign, but timeless and rooted.

 And it was even more special because our honourable PM Shri Narendra Modi Ji has been one of the first global leaders to give lifestyle and preventive health the stage it deserves.

From yoga to sunlight, from stillness to service, India’s always had these answers.

Here’s how you can start bringing them into your day:
☀️ Start with nature. Wake up, step into natural light, walk barefoot, breathe deeply, these aren’t trends, they’re time-tested tools.
 🧘🏽 Build inner peace. Through prayer, pranayama, or Surya Namaskar, whatever helps you go inward.
 🌀 Reframe stress. It’s not always a threat; it’s often a challenge, inviting growth.
 📚 Keep learning. Stay open, stay humble, wisdom often comes from unexpected places.
 🤝 Connect and give. Whether through volunteering or simple kindness, acts of service are powerful medicine.
 🎧 Guard your mind. Just like food, what you feed your mind matters; choose content that aligns with your values.
 🙏🏽 Gratitude always. Especially on tough days. It shifts perspective, softens the heart, and brings clarity.

This isn’t about a perfect routine. It’s about returning to what’s always worked.
 Small, consistent steps that help you evolve, mentally, emotionally, and spiritually.
Heal in India. Made in India. Rooted in India.

We’ve also compiled a comprehensive booklet the Bharat Lifestyle Plan that was presented to our honourable Prime Minister for all of you to see, download, learn, share and implement in your lives.

Download your copy (available in Hindi, English, Marathi, Gujarati) from the link in bio.

Calcium supplements…Calcium chewable tablets…Dairy 💊

You want and need K2 to put the calcium into@your bones , you don’t want it in your joints and arteries causing problems 

While these might seem like the best approaches to getting strong bones, consuming them is a wasted effort (rather harmful) if you are deficient in:
Vitamin D3 ☀️ (which every 1 in 2 people are!)
Vitamin K2
Magnesium ⚡

Bone is not all calcium
Each of the above minerals and vitamins are just as important to form the Bone Matrix. They work together as a team synergistically, along with calcium to keep your bones strong and healthy from childhood through the older years.

If we consume too much calcium without sufficient magnesium, Vitamin D3 & K2, the excess calcium is not utilized correctly and may actually become toxic, causing calcification of arteries, bone spurs and heart complications! ❤️‍🩹

So, more calcium & dairy doesn’t mean stronger, healthier bones. You need a healthy bone matrix for strong, young bones, which further determines your bone density and strength.

If you are on treatments like radiation, chemotherapy or taking medications, birth control pills, hormonal treatments, estrogen blockers then these too deteriorate bone density. Thus as a part of your strategy to manage side-effects, it’s important to supplement or at least focus on food sources that make up your bone matrix. 🍽️

	•	A point I missed - importance of sleep for bone health… deep restful sleep 💤 is when bones get stronger and processes like bone remodelling and repair occurs.

Even if you have had a knee/hip replacement you still have to take care of your bones.

A quality life as you age doesn’t mean a good bank balance, access to insurance, doctors and other facilities, but also strong and healthy bones.

Build healthy bones because we will always need them.

Disclaimer: For many medical conditions, you might be required to take calcium supplements. Speak to your doctor about supplements that do not just have calcium but the complete formulation that help build bone matrix.

You feel tired all the time.
Your energy dips for no reason.
You’ve checked your bloodwork.
Your hemoglobin is normal.
Your doctor says things look fine.

But your hair is falling.
Your nails are brittle.
Your skin looks dull.
You’re foggy. You’re restless. 

You’re not imagining it.
There’s something deeper going on.

Have you looked at your ferritin levels?
Because we’ve seen this with so many clients, the problem isn’t always in the obvious markers.
It’s in the reserves.

Ferritin is your iron bank.
Hemoglobin can look perfect while ferritin is quietly running on empty.
This is what we call iron deficiency without anemia (IDWA), which is an early red flag.

This is why a holistic approach matters.
Because health isn’t just about fixing the obvious.
It’s about understanding the systems underneath the symptoms.

Medicine is powerful, and always take what your doctor prescribes.
But pair it with a lifestyle plan:
→ Check your nutrition
→ Understand absorption
→ Address gut health
→ Work on rest and recovery
→ And always recheck.

Sometimes the answer is that simple.
And sometimes it takes zooming out, not digging deeper.

That’s the beauty of integrative and lifestyle medicine — it doesn’t replace, it complements.

This video is a perfect example of why dash cams are so important. It shows a driver deliberately backing into another car to stage an accident and make it look like the rear driver is at fault. These scams are becoming more common, and without evidence, you could end up paying the price.

Here’s why a dash cam is a must:
1️⃣ It’s Your Witness: A dash cam captures exactly what happened, so you’re not stuck relying on someone else’s word.
2️⃣ Stops Fraudsters in Their Tracks: With video proof, it’s nearly impossible for scammers to pull off these kinds of stunts.
3️⃣ Gives You Peace of Mind: Knowing you’re protected takes a huge weight off your shoulders when you’re on the road.
4️⃣ Get Legal Help: If you’re caught in a situation like this, don’t fight it alone. An attorney can help you use your evidence to make your case and protect your rights.

A dash cam might seem like a small thing, but it can make all the difference when it comes to situations like this. Stay smart, stay safe, and stay protected. 🚗💡

Road rage incidents can quickly escalate into dangerous situations. Protect yourself and others by following these tips:

1️⃣ Give Yourself Time: Running late? Plan ahead to avoid rushing and unnecessary stress.

2️⃣ Stay Focused: Keep your attention on driving, not on aggressive drivers. Ignore rude gestures or honking—don’t engage.

3️⃣ Practice Patience: Let faster or aggressive drivers pass. It’s not worth risking your safety to “win” on the road.

4️⃣ Control Your Emotions: If you feel frustrated, take deep breaths, listen to calming music, or pull over safely to cool off.

5️⃣ Report Dangerous Drivers: If someone is driving recklessly, report them to authorities—your safety comes first.

Understanding the difference between personal injury and workers’ compensation can make a big difference in your recovery journey and the support you receive. Here’s a quick breakdown:

➡️ Personal Injury: Applies if you’re hurt outside of work (like in a car accident or at a store), and someone else may be at fault.

➡️ Workers’ Compensation: Covers injuries that happen on the job, regardless of fault, with medical and wage benefits.

This Mother’s Day and Mental Health Awareness Month and I want to thank Mavi for being there for me in every moment- not just the happy ones. 

As many of you know I battle depression and while I am still learning to live with it, having Mavi in my life has really helped. 

It’s like an ocean… it goes out and it comes in. It can be all consuming and when it hits I am plagued with fatigue and emptiness. During that time nothing seems to shine. I’m very lucky that I always have Mavi by my side begging for a walk or willing to cuddle when I am a prisoner to my bed. Together we always get to the other side.
 
I partnered for #MentalHealthAwarenessMonth with @nulopetfood in support of the silent battle so many of us are fighting. Awareness is the first step, then from there it’s dissolving the stigma that surrounds mental health and keeps us hiding our private battles. If you are struggling- just know that you are not alone and there is always a light at the end of the tunnel.

Excited to finally share our latest initiative over at @officialblackwallstreet! Over the past 10 years (🤯), one of the biggest lessons I’ve learned is the priceless value of community. My sanity has been kept intact thanks to the Black founders in my circle who remind me that I’m not alone in this journey. We’re all facing similar challenges, and we can navigate them more effectively together.

Issa Rae once said it best, “We have a tendency to try to network up, but it’s really about networking across. Who’s next to you? Who’s struggling? Who’s in the trenches with you? Build with them.” There’s so much power in building with our peers.

This is why I’m so proud to introduce the OBWS Founders Club—a community for ambitious Black entrepreneurs (& aspiring founders) to intentionally connect, share resources, support, and uplift each other. 🙌🏾

If you’re a Black founder or aspiring founder looking for a supportive network, real connections, and access to resources, this is for you. Learn more and apply through the link in my bio or at founders.obws.com

On May 1st 1950, Gwendolyn Brooks made history as the first African American to win a Pulitzer Prize, receiving the honor for her poetry collection Annie Allen, a coming-of-age portrait of a young Black girl navigating love, war, and womanhood.⁠
⁠
Born in Topeka, Kansas, and raised in Chicago, Brooks began writing at a young age and published her first poem at just 13.  Her work wasn’t just poetry, it was protest, pride, and power. From We Real Cool to The Bean Eaters, Brooks told stories that mattered, in a voice that couldn’t be ignored.⁠
⁠
She later became the Poet Laureate of Illinois and the Library of Congress’ Consultant in Poetry, blazing a trail for Black writers across the nation.⁠
⁠
👑 A literary icon.⁠

On April 19, 1978, Max Robinson made history as the first Black anchor of a network newscast, joining ABC World News Tonight in 1978 and breaking barriers in American journalism.⁠
⁠
Born in Richmond, Virginia, in 1939, Robinson faced systemic racism early in life, including being expelled from college for staging a protest against segregation. Still, he pushed forward, studying at Virginia Union University, an HBCU, and later launching his broadcasting career at a local TV station where his image was initially hidden behind a screen to conceal his race.⁠
⁠
But Robinson refused to be silenced or sidelined.⁠
⁠
He rose to national prominence not just for his commanding presence and journalistic excellence, but for using his platform to speak truth to power and advocate for more honest representation of Black communities in media. 👏🏾⁠
⁠

52 years ago today, this Black woman made history and paved the way for generations of leaders to come. 🗳️⁠
⁠
In 1973, Lelia Foley was elected mayor of Taft, Oklahoma, becoming the first Black woman elected mayor in the United States. A divorced mother of five living on welfare, Lelia Foley didn’t wait for change, she decided to become the change. ⁠
⁠
After being inspired by a visit to her community from civil rights leader Shirley Chisholm, Foley raised just $200, ran for office, and won. Let her story remind you: no background or barrier is too big when purpose and power align. 👏🏾⁠

On this day 57 years ago, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. delivered his final, prophetic speech: 'I've Been to the Mountaintop.' ✊🏾🔥"⁠
⁠
Standing before a crowd in Memphis on April 3, 1968, Dr. King spoke with an urgency that still resonates today. He reflected on the struggles of the Civil Rights Movement, the fight for economic justice, and the promise of a better future. His words on economic power and collective action still resonate today.⁠
⁠
💬 “We've got to strengthen Black institutions. I call upon you to take your money out of the banks downtown and deposit your money in Tri-State Bank—we want a ‘bank-in’ movement in Memphis.”⁠
⁠
Dr. King understood that economic empowerment was key to liberation. He urged Black communities to invest in their own financial institutions, boycott businesses that exploited Black workers, and build collective economic strength. His message is a reminder that where we spend and invest our money is a powerful tool for change.⁠
⁠
Less than 24 hours later, he was assassinated, but his words and mission live on. Dr. King's vision for justice, equality, and economic empowerment remains as powerful and necessary as ever. #BlackExcellence

🗳️ 'The time has come for Black people to fight back in self-defense whenever and wherever they are unjustly and unlawfully attacked.'⁠

💡 He challenged systemic oppression and called for unity beyond religious or ideological differences, stating:⁠
"Whether you are a Christian or a Muslim or a nationalist, we all have the same problem. They don’t hang you because you're a Baptist; they hang you because you’re Black!"⁠
⁠
📢 Malcolm X urged the Black community to use the ballot wisely. Demand real change from politicians or refuse to support those who don’t serve Black interests. His message remains as relevant today as it was in 1964.⁠

41 years ago today, Coach John Thompson 🕊️ became the FIRST Black head coach to win an NCAA basketball championship! Leading Georgetown University to victory in 1984, Thompson not only secured a historic title but also paved the way for future Black coaches in college basketball.⁠
⁠
Born and raised in Washington, D.C., Thompson was a dominant force on the court before stepping into coaching. A 6’10” center, he played college ball at Providence College, where he led the team to the NIT Championship in 1963 and became an All-American. After a brief stint in the NBA with the Boston Celtics—winning two championships as a backup to Bill Russell—he transitioned to coaching, taking over Georgetown’s basketball program in 1972.⁠
⁠
Thompson transformed the Hoyas into a powerhouse, mentoring future NBA legends like Patrick Ewing, Alonzo Mourning, and Allen Iverson. Off the court, he was a fierce advocate for Black student-athletes, famously walking out on an NCAA meeting in protest of rules that he felt unfairly targeted underprivileged players. 👏🏾 #BlackExcellence #BlackHistory⁠
⁠
May he continue to rest in power. 🕊️

On this day in 1965, the historic Selma to Montgomery March culminated as thousands of demonstrators arrived at the Alabama State Capitol, marking a pivotal moment in the fight for voting rights. ⁠
⁠
Led by Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., the marchers embarked on a five-day, 54-mile journey. Under federal protection, they covered about 12 miles a day and slept in fields and makeshift camps along U.S. Route 80, enduring physical exhaustion and threats to demand equal voting rights for African Americans.⁠
⁠
The march followed earlier attempts that were met with violent opposition, notably the events of "Bloody Sunday" on March 7, 1965, when peaceful protesters were brutally attacked at the Edmund Pettus Bridge. Despite these challenges, the marchers persevered, and their efforts contributed significantly to the passage of the Voting Rights Act of 1965, a landmark achievement in the Civil Rights Movement. ✊🏾 #BlackHistory⁠
⁠

The dessert of your dreams. 🍫✨⁠
The Shasta Zero Sugar Cho•Co•lat De•lite Mini Bundt Cakes—made with our rich, fizzy Zero Sugar chocolate soda—is perfect for sweet cravings, celebrations, or just because.⁠
⁠
Ingredients:⁠
⁠
For the cakes:⁠
2 cups all-purpose flour⁠
1/2 teaspoon baking powder⁠
1 teaspoon vanilla extract⁠
1/4 cup vegetable oil (plus extra for greasing)⁠
2 eggs⁠
1/3 cup cacao powder⁠
2 tablespoons honey⁠
1/3 cup Shasta Zero Sugar Cho•Co•lat De•lite⁠
⁠
For the chocolate drizzle:⁠
1/3 cup dark chocolate, melted⁠
1 tablespoon Zero Sugar Cho•Co•lat De•lite⁠
⁠
Fresh fruits for garnish ⁠
⁠
⁠
Steps:⁠
Preheat oven to 350°F. Lightly grease mini bundt pans (or a large cake pan) with vegetable oil. Mix flour and baking powder in a bowl. Add vanilla extract, vegetable oil, eggs, cacao powder, honey, and Shasta Zero Sugar Cho•Co•lat De•lite. Whisk until smooth. Pour batter evenly into the greased pans. Bake for 15 minutes (or 25–30 minutes for a large cake) until a toothpick inserted in the center comes out clean. Let cool completely. Melt dark chocolate and stir in Shasta Zero Sugar Cho•Co•lat De•lite until smooth. Drizzle chocolate over cooled cakes. Garnish with fresh fruits. Enjoy these soft and chocolatey treats any time of the day!⁠
⁠

Start saving early for your down payment and closing costs! 💸 As we close out Financial Literacy Month, here’s a review of key steps for potential homebuyers: 

STOP #1: Check your credit reports and FICO score. A strong credit score opens doors to better loan rates and approval. 💳 STOP #2: Lowering your DTI shows lenders you're financially stable and ready for homeownership. 🏠 Pay down debts and watch your spending habits.
STOP #3: Each new account can affect your credit score and debt ratio, making it harder to secure a mortgage. Stay focused on your homeownership goals! 🏡💳 
STOP #4: Pre-approval from a mortgage lender helps you understand your budget, strengthens your offer and shows sellers (and real estate agents) that you're a serious buyer! 🏡🔑 
STOP #5: Plan your monthly budget for the new home, including taxes, utilities, HOA fees, and maintenance costs. 🏠

And finally...

STOP #6: We’ve reached the last step before making an offer and signing the dotted line. As you review house listings, use our Closing Cost estimator to ensure the houses you show your real estate agent are within your budget. Being financially prepared means fewer surprises during the homebuying process. Aim for at least 20% down to avoid extra fees! 🏠💰 This concludes our Financial Literacy Month roadmap, but these tips are valid no matter when you’re starting your real estate journey. For more articles, guides and resources on the real estate process and title insurance, visit stewart.com/home.

Real Estate FAQ: How long does closing take? 

From the moment your offer is accepted to getting the keys to your new house, the closing process involves many steps to finalize the purchase. The average closing on a house takes 30 to 60 days. Why does it take so long? Many steps go into a closing, including title search and examination, document preparation, loan settlement and more. Title issues, low appraisals and renegotiations can delay your closing. 

Have more questions about the closing process? Reach out to your local Stewart Title team and visit stewart.com/home for more information about title insurance, the home buying process and more.

“And as we approach October 7th, once again, it is clear that we are all still in the trauma. It is in the giant holes still in our hearts left by the loss of so many of our people, including four beloved members of the TY community: Gili, Yuval, Re'em, and Laor. It remains in the constant fear we have for the lives of Omer Neutra and all of the hostages whose fate and future remain unclear. And it remains in the ongoing war that is taking the lives of our friends and family in Israel, leaving communities in a constant state of danger, causing intolerable and unimaginable suffering throughout the region, and creating deep unease amongst Jews around the world.”

Read more from our Executive Director, David Weinstein, at the link in our bio.

A person that you can’t miss,
Who brought joy to all the chanichim, someone who at 18 was already mature, charismatic, ethical, and captivating for his age. Someone you never forget.

The municipality of Ramat Gan commemorates its fallen through paths and streets. Tomorrow, a ceremony will take place to unveil the path named after Yuval.
Yuval fell on October 9th during a pursuit of a cell that had infiltrated Sderot. He was killed in an encounter with another cell that was lying in ambush near Sha’ar HaNegev Junction. In other words, he fought from October 7th amidst the chaos in the surrounding communities to stop it. That’s heroism.

When you meet someone like that after the army at a summer camp in the U.S., you don’t know you’re standing before a hero, but the truth is there were signs that he was something special and different.
Yuval was in Garin Atid two or three years after me and we were ‘Mishlat’ together at Camp Tel Yehuda. Even then, we were impressed by this mature 18-year-old guy who had Amit, the girl he loved, who later became his wife and the mother of his child.
He would play music for everyone, a cute and funny scouting specialist . One day, we were assigned to make sure the campers drank enough water during the sports competition (the Maccabiah). Together with two other funny staff members , Plotkin and Monica, we decided to turn it into something else—not just handing out water but getting into characters and creating a water frenzy for the campers. We created a doll that became our symbol, managed to secretly place it on the roof of the Beit ha’am, and caused chaos (it posed a danger to the participants, and they had to bring in a huge ladder to take it down). I am grateful that I got to have days like that with you.

As for the second gratitude , for leaving your home with Amit in Ramat Gan to go fight the evil terrorists, I don’t even know how to say it.
The city of Ramat Gan commemorates you, and the family will participate in the ceremony dedicating a path in your memory in Shaul Park. A path, in a beloved park. You will likely continue to lead people in your path .
Dear Yuval, may your memory be blessed, and thank you.
@telyehudah
One thing you can count at Tel Yehudah: plenty of rikud! We love having rikud after Havdalah on Saturday nights. It’s the perfect way to come together and celebrate the end of Shabbat!

Elevating pasta night with a twist: Parmigiano and matcha tea cream, sweet apricots, and a pop of pink peppercorns—best enjoyed with family, friends, or your loved one. 

Ingredients (serves 4):
400g of PASTA LOVE
150g grated Parmesan cheese 
300ml cooking cream 
50g powdered matcha tea 
100g Vermouth (or balsamic vinegar)
5ml soy sauce 
5 dried apricots 
Pink peppercorns to taste
Extra virgin olive oil to taste
Salt to taste

Method:
1. Boil the vermouth and let it reduce over low heat until it reaches an almost syrupy consistency. Add soy sauce to intensify the flavor.
2. Put the cream in a small pan, add the Parmesan cheese, and heat over low heat until the Parmesan is melted. Strain (or blend) to obtain a smooth sauce, then add the matcha tea and mix.
3. Slice the apricot and set aside until plating.
4. Cook the pasta in salted boiling water until "al dente," then toss it in a pan with a drizzle of extra virgin olive oil and some cooking water, adjusting the salt.
5. Arrange the pasta on the plate and evenly distribute the Parmesan cream, a few drops of vermouth or balsamic vinegar, the sliced apricots, and the pink pepper crushed with your fingers.

#ShapesOfLove #Barilla

Saffron, fennel, and prawns: an irresistible combination to enjoy with those who make every meal special! 

Ingredients (serves 4):
400g of PASTA LOVE
1 shallot 
8 red prawns 
350g fennel 
1 lime zest
500ml water 
50ml extra virgin olive oil
1 sachet of saffron 
Salt and black pepper, 
Cuttlefish ink drops to garnish 
Wild fennel (or dill), thyme, to taste 

Method: 
1. In a small pot, heat the oil and add the sliced shallot and fennel (cleaned, washed, and diced). Sauté the vegetables for 2-3 minutes, then cover them with water and let them stew for about 20 minutes. Season with salt and pepper, add the saffron, and blend to obtain a thick cream.
2. Clean the red prawns by removing the intestines. Place them on a baking sheet with lime zest, salt, pepper, thyme, and a drizzle of extra virgin olive oil. Cook them at 100 degrees Celsius for 7-8 minutes.
3. Cook the pasta in salted boiling water, drain it “al dente,” and toss it with the fennel cream, diluted with a bit of cooking water, and the diced peeled lime.
4. Plate the pasta and add the red prawns.
5. Garnish with a few drops of squid in and some sprigs of wild fennel (or dill) and thyme, and finish with a grind of pepper.
6. Serve and enjoy! 

#ShapesOfLove #Barilla

Spatial computing goes beyond the traditional flat screens we interact with. It's an umbrella term encompassing technologies like augmented reality (AR) and virtual reality (VR) that aim to seamlessly blend the digital and physical worlds. Imagine furniture appearing in your living room virtually to see if it fits or receiving repair instructions overlaid on a broken machine through your glasses. 
 
Spatial computing uses real-time spatial data and allows interaction with digital elements within our physical environment. The demand for spatial computing specialists, including AR/VR developers, 3D artists, and experienced designers, has surged by 45%, indicating a booming job market in this innovative field.

Ever feel that urge to push tasks until the last minute? Science explains it with the 'Procrastination Equation'! This formula reveals a battle between motivation and impulsiveness. The key? Understand the equation – boost confidence, find value, minimize distractions, and set closer deadlines.

💥From Queens, NY to Atlanta, GA —> there’s a new coffee shop now open in Midtown Atlanta! 💥 

If you love exploring the coffee scene in and around Atlanta area, follow @atlantacoffeeshops, and subscribe to the Atlanta Coffee Shops (ACS) newsletter to stay in the know on all things ATL coffee—at the link in bio! 👀

Opened last week at a prime location of West Peachtree St. and 12th Streets (inside the @google building) is For Five Coffee Roasters (@forfive), a Queens, NYC-based roaster + coffee shop. The Atlanta location has been a long time coming, and ACS was aware of its pending opening going back to May 2021. The pandemic plans fell through, but the company pushed on and opened its doors in the ATL in late February 2025. The Atlanta location was worth waiting for — it is For Five’s biggest café by square footage (3,700 s.f.) across 30+ stores and represents a new flagship in Atlanta and the Southeast.

The interior features a modern aesthetic and a hotel-like lobby/interior. There is plenty of seating across the bar area, individual, and communal tables. Free Wi-Fi is available, and the coffee shop is open 7AM to 7PM daily. With this new ATL location, For Five is elevating every detail in a café experience.

As for coffee: the espresso here is Roc Center Espresso blend from @forfive (a blend of Brazilian, Colombian, and Indonesian coffee beans; tasting notes of lemon zest and cocoa).

A must-order on the coffee menu is the Freddo Cappuccino—get it iced—as that is a rare item to see on a coffee menu in Atlanta. 

The coffee shop also features a full assortment of pastries and a lunch menu—these would be worth exploring over multiple days in Midtown—as well as a popular stuffed cookie 🍪 menu (IYKYK).

At Gemelli, we believe in making SIBO testing as accessible as possible. With the Trio-Smart breath test, you can save time and money by testing at home before committing to a GI visit. Based on your results, you can make an informed decision about the next steps in finding the right provider(s) for your treatment.

SIBO treatments are not one-size-fits-all; often, a positive test means both antibiotics and dietary changes may be needed. We're grateful for providers who specialize in these necessary diet modifications, like @marriedtohealth's Dahlia Marin, RDN, LD, CGN, who helps so many patients with their immediate symptoms, while getting to the root cause. SIBO treatment is highly personalized and may need adjustments over time, and having a provider who cares about your whole well-being is crucial to your healing journey. 

We are honored to support and collaborate with those who put so much effort into helping their patients. Your health matters, and finding a provider who understands that is integral to your recovery. 💜

#SIBO #IMO #ISO #GutHealth #TrioSmart #MarriedToHealth #PatientCare #HealWithEachMeal

Tired of taking endless trips... to the bathroom?🚽
We are delighted that @mollypelletier.rd, a registered dietitian specializing in acid reflux and digestive health, and the owner of FLORA Nutrition, recommends our Trio-Smart 3-Gas Breath Test to her patients!

Happy @WorldMicrobiomeDay! 🌎🦠 This year's theme is diet.

Here are three diets often used to manage SIBO and IBS symptoms:

1. The Elemental Diet:  A restrictive diet that replaces food and drinks with liquid or powder formulas that are easy to digest and provide a complete nutritional profile. The formulas break down proteins, fats, and carbohydrates into their basic building blocks, such as amino acids, fatty acids, and sugars, and combine them with vitamins, minerals, and electrolytes. Check out @elementaldiet

2. The Low Fermentation Diet: A restrictive diet that aims to help people with small intestinal bacterial overgrowth or irritable bowel syndrome. The diet limits fermentable carbohydrates that can feed bacteria. It also includes meal timing guidelines to allow the gut to empty out between meals. Check out @goodlfeofficial @mastprogram 

3. The Low FODMAP Diet: A restrictive diet that limits foods that contain fermentable oligosaccharides, disaccharides, monosaccharides, and polyols (FODMAPs). FODMAPs are short-chain carbohydrates that are poorly absorbed by the small intestine and ferment in the colon. Check out @monashfodmap

Remember, always consult your doctor before trying a new diet. Here's to a healthy microbiome!

Navigating SIBO symptoms can be tricky as they often mimic other GI conditions. Symptoms vary from person to person but can include:

 #SIBO #GutHealth #TrioSmart #SIBOSymptoms #GutSymptoms #Diarrhea #Bloating #Constipation

Normally, the small intestine contains relatively few bacteria compared to the large intestine or colon. However, with SIBO, bacteria from the colon migrate and take up residence in the small intestine, leading to an overgrowth. 🧫🔬

This overpopulation of bacteria starts feasting on your dietary nutrients before your body can fully digest and absorb them. As the bacteria consume the food passing through, they produce excess gases as a byproduct. It's this gaseous overproduction that leads to the hallmark SIBO symptoms like bloating, abdominal pain, diarrhea, and flatulence. 💨🙁

When bacteria exist in their proper territories and quantities, digestion hums along undisturbed. But when their balance gets disrupted through migration and overgrowth, SIBO's unpleasant digestive woes can take over your daily life.

Learn more on the Trio-Smart Website! 💜

It's true...in fact, food poisoning is the leading known cause of IBS! 🤯 
According to the CDC, 48 million people get food poisoning every year in America. In a review conducted at the Mayo Clinic of over 40 research studies, 11% (1 in 9) will develop IBS after food poisoning.

That means this year in America alone, 5 million people will develop post-infectious IBS! Patients with post-infectious IBS are four times more likely to contract food poisoning again. Additionally, if you do get food poisoning again, it can significantly worsen the symptoms of your post-infectious IBS. 

Post-infectious IBS presents itself as IBS-D or IBS-M. Therefore, you might have post-infectious IBS if:
💩 You have chronic diarrhea, traveler’s diarrhea, or mixed diarrhea and constipation symptoms.
😫 You have abdominal pain and bloating.
🩸 You have no other serious symptoms like blood in your stool.
🤮 You have had food poisoning at some point in the past. (Note: Patients may not accurately recall whether they have had food poisoning.)

💜 Test yourself for post-infectious IBS with IBS-Smart, our at-home IBS test! Link In Bio.

Sometimes we return to the things we love to remind us of who we are. 💙

This past year brought some of the biggest changes of my life — a diagnosis of ADHD, depression, and C-PTSD, along with navigating a lot of new and more intensive ways of coping and healing. I wanted a goal that was big, uncomfortable, and meaningful. A challenge to hold me accountable and reconnect me with running and myself. The NYC Marathon became that goal, @brasforgirlsorg became the “why”, and running once again became my safe place to land.

Excited to finally share our latest initiative over at @officialblackwallstreet! Over the past 10 years (🤯), one of the biggest lessons I’ve learned is the priceless value of community. My sanity has been kept intact thanks to the Black founders in my circle who remind me that I’m not alone in this journey. We’re all facing similar challenges, and we can navigate them more effectively together.

Issa Rae once said it best, “We have a tendency to try to network up, but it’s really about networking across. Who’s next to you? Who’s struggling? Who’s in the trenches with you? Build with them.” There’s so much power in building with our peers.

Born in Topeka, Kansas, and raised in Chicago, Brooks began writing at a young age and published her first poem at just 13.  Her work wasn’t just poetry, it was protest, pride, and power. From We Real Cool to The Bean Eaters, Brooks told stories that mattered, in a voice that couldn’t be ignored.⁠
⁠
She later became the Poet Laureate of Illinois and the Library of Congress’ Consultant in Poetry, blazing a trail for Black writers across the nation.⁠
⁠
👑 A literary icon.⁠
⁠

On April 19, 1978, Max Robinson made history as the first Black anchor of a network newscast, joining ABC World News Tonight in 1978 and breaking barriers in American journalism.⁠
⁠
Born in Richmond, Virginia, in 1939, Robinson faced systemic racism early in life, including being expelled from college for staging a protest against segregation. Still, he pushed forward, studying at Virginia Union University, an HBCU, and later launching his broadcasting career at a local TV station where his image was initially hidden behind a screen to conceal his race.⁠
⁠
But Robinson refused to be silenced or sidelined.⁠
⁠
He rose to national prominence not just for his commanding presence and journalistic excellence, but for using his platform to speak truth to power and advocate for more honest representation of Black communities in media. 👏🏾⁠
⁠

52 years ago today, this Black woman made history and paved the way for generations of leaders to come. 🗳️⁠
⁠
In 1973, Lelia Foley was elected mayor of Taft, Oklahoma, becoming the first Black woman elected mayor in the United States. A divorced mother of five living on welfare, Lelia Foley didn’t wait for change, she decided to become the change. ⁠
⁠
After being inspired by a visit to her community from civil rights leader Shirley Chisholm, Foley raised just $200, ran for office, and won. Let her story remind you: no background or barrier is too big when purpose and power align. 👏🏾⁠

On this day 57 years ago, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. delivered his final, prophetic speech: 'I've Been to the Mountaintop.' ✊🏾🔥"⁠
⁠
Standing before a crowd in Memphis on April 3, 1968, Dr. King spoke with an urgency that still resonates today. He reflected on the struggles of the Civil Rights Movement, the fight for economic justice, and the promise of a better future. His words on economic power and collective action still resonate today.⁠
⁠
💬 “We've got to strengthen Black institutions. I call upon you to take your money out of the banks downtown and deposit your money in Tri-State Bank—we want a ‘bank-in’ movement in Memphis.”⁠
⁠
Dr. King understood that economic empowerment was key to liberation. He urged Black communities to invest in their own financial institutions, boycott businesses that exploited Black workers, and build collective economic strength. His message is a reminder that where we spend and invest our money is a powerful tool for change.⁠
⁠
Less than 24 hours later, he was assassinated, but his words and mission live on. Dr. King's vision for justice, equality, and economic empowerment remains as powerful and necessary as ever. #BlackExcellence

On this day 61 years ago, Malcolm X delivered his iconic 'Ballot or the Bullet' speech in Cleveland, Ohio, on April 3, 1964. 🔥 His message was clear: Black Americans must use their political power strategically and demand their civil rights.⁠
⁠
🗳️ 'The time has come for Black people to fight back in self-defense whenever and wherever they are unjustly and unlawfully attacked.'⁠
⁠
💡 He challenged systemic oppression and called for unity beyond religious or ideological differences, stating:⁠
"Whether you are a Christian or a Muslim or a nationalist, we all have the same problem. They don’t hang you because you're a Baptist; they hang you because you’re Black!"⁠
⁠
📢 Malcolm X urged the Black community to use the ballot wisely. Demand real change from politicians or refuse to support those who don’t serve Black interests. His message remains as relevant today as it was in 1964.⁠
⁠
✊🏾 Do you think his words still apply today? Drop your thoughts in the comments! 👇🏾⁠

41 years ago today, Coach John Thompson 🕊️ became the FIRST Black head coach to win an NCAA basketball championship! Leading Georgetown University to victory in 1984, Thompson not only secured a historic title but also paved the way for future Black coaches in college basketball.⁠
⁠
Born and raised in Washington, D.C., Thompson was a dominant force on the court before stepping into coaching. A 6’10” center, he played college ball at Providence College, where he led the team to the NIT Championship in 1963 and became an All-American. After a brief stint in the NBA with the Boston Celtics—winning two championships as a backup to Bill Russell—he transitioned to coaching, taking over Georgetown’s basketball program in 1972.⁠
⁠
Thompson transformed the Hoyas into a powerhouse, mentoring future NBA legends like Patrick Ewing, Alonzo Mourning, and Allen Iverson. Off the court, he was a fierce advocate for Black student-athletes, famously walking out on an NCAA meeting in protest of rules that he felt unfairly targeted underprivileged players. 👏🏾 #BlackExcellence #BlackHistory⁠
⁠
May he continue to rest in power. 🕊️

On this day in 1965, the historic Selma to Montgomery March culminated as thousands of demonstrators arrived at the Alabama State Capitol, marking a pivotal moment in the fight for voting rights. ⁠
⁠
Led by Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., the marchers embarked on a five-day, 54-mile journey. Under federal protection, they covered about 12 miles a day and slept in fields and makeshift camps along U.S. Route 80, enduring physical exhaustion and threats to demand equal voting rights for African Americans.⁠
⁠
The march followed earlier attempts that were met with violent opposition, notably the events of "Bloody Sunday" on March 7, 1965, when peaceful protesters were brutally attacked at the Edmund Pettus Bridge. Despite these challenges, the marchers persevered, and their efforts contributed significantly to the passage of the Voting Rights Act of 1965, a landmark achievement in the Civil Rights Movement. ✊🏾 #BlackHistory⁠
⁠

A 2016 study in the British Journal of Psychology uncovered an unexpected link between intelligence and happiness: while frequent social interaction tends to boost life satisfaction for most people, the opposite holds true for those with higher intelligence.

Researchers found that highly intelligent individuals often feel less satisfied when socializing too frequently. Instead, they tend to prefer solitude, deep focus, and meaningful, goal-oriented pursuits over casual interactions. This aligns with the “savanna theory of happiness,” which suggests our brains still respond to social settings shaped by evolutionary history—and that smarter individuals are better equipped to navigate modern environments with fewer social dependencies.

In essence, it’s not that intelligent people dislike connection—it’s that they seek quality over quantity. For them, peace, purpose, and depth matter more than constant company.

#study #pubity #viral

Christopher Nolan’s upcoming epic The Odyssey will make history as the first commercial feature film shot entirely on Imax film cameras. 🎥🎬

While Nolan has long championed the format—using it for large portions of films like Dunkirk, Tenet, and Oppenheimer—this marks the first time a movie will be filmed entirely in Imax, on 70mm film, from beginning to end.

Following the success of Oppenheimer, which earned over $190 million on Imax screens alone, Nolan challenged Imax to improve its technology. The result: new Imax film cameras that are 30% quieter, significantly lighter, and backed by faster scanning and processing for quicker access to dailies. “If you can solve the problems, I’ll shoot the whole thing in Imax,” Nolan told Imax CEO Rich Gelfond. Now that promise is coming to life.

The new camera system is currently reserved for The Odyssey, but Imax plans to make the gear available to other directors after Nolan finishes the film. Interest is already surging, with a record number of films in 2025 either using Imax cameras or filming specifically for the format—including Sinners, Mission: Impossible – The Final Reckoning, and Formula One starring Brad Pitt.

While studying at Howard University in the late ’90s, Chadwick Boseman was accepted into a prestigious summer acting program at Oxford—but couldn’t afford the tuition.

His professor, Phylicia Rashad, quietly reached out to a friend: Denzel Washington.

Without seeking recognition, Denzel paid for Boseman and his classmates to attend.

Years later, at the 2019 AFI Awards, Boseman finally revealed the story, saying:
“There is no Black Panther without Denzel Washington.”

At the Black Panther premiere, Denzel joked: “You owe me money. I came to collect.”
A full-circle moment between a silent mentor—and a star who never forgot.

Do you know which countries benefit the most when there is a war in the world?

There are two ways to look at this...

The first kind of countries are those that are the world’s largest suppliers of defence equipment - it’s the US, Russia, China, Israel...

But the second type is most interesting... these are the neutral countries which don’t take sides, maintain absolute safety of its people, and become the place where the millionaires from war struck economies start transferring their wealth...

They have the highest reward to risk ratio in such uncertain times, and include Switzerland and Singapore... but the top of the list is Dubai in the UAE...

It’s a safe hub for capital and people... and benefited during the Iran-Iraq war, the Kuwait War, the America-Iraq war, and the Russia Ukraine war... 

And how they’ve enabled it is a masterclass on how small economies are run...

Since Dubai had practically no income from oil, it realized it was bang in the middle of Europe, Africa and Asia and thus, started luxury airlines like Emirates and Etihad to just give people free layovers on long flights.

So you have global travellers (the rich) stopping here, they realize they could set up trading companies with zero taxes...

So those companies started setting up... you need labour, which comes easy from Pakistan, Sri Lanka and African countries...

You need to get your family, you get a golden visa...

And when the rich start banking their international payments here, the money funds luxury real estate, luxury retail, and makes it a fabulous holiday home cum business destination for the wealthy.

Such that it has the highest density of millionaires in the world. Almost 70k millionaires for a population of just 3.5 Million!

And they very strategically peg their currency to the dollar, thus removing currency volatility altogether!

People were expecting Dubai real estate to cool off, but the current economic climate may lead it to continue for another couple of years.

While most people take investing advice from Warren Buffett... I like referring to his advice on hiring...

He says there are only three things you should look out for while hiring people -

1/ Integrity
2/ Intelligence
3/ Energy

If they don’t have the first one, the other two will kill you.

Now, most interviews test number two and three - as both intelligence and energy can be perceived and felt from the resume, and their demeanour.

It’s testing the integrity that takes the most amount of effort...

To do this, you need to ask them two questions:

1/ Tell me about a time when upholding your principles cost you something valuable... and 

2/ Describe a situation where you made a significant mistake at work. How did you handle it?

The biggest red flags in an answer would be if they blame the failure on the team and can’t take ownership... or even if they have no failure story to share, or give non specific vague answers.

Someone who gives you a weakness that is actually a strength is the biggest bullcrapper on the planet because you want someone who can be real and own up to their genuine shortcomings.

Combine the above with two solid references of people you can speak with and check the above... It could be superiors, peers, but someone of credibility who can validate it.

You could ask the references to rate the candidate’s trustworthiness on a scale of 1 to 10, and if they give him an 8 or 9, ask why they deducted a point and what would make them worthy of a full 10.

While the Indian passport gives you visa free access to about 60 countries, the Portugal passport gives you 188 countries visa free, including US, Canada, UK and the whole of Europe.

To be eligible, you have to visit Portugal for just 7 days per year, and maintain an investment in their country for 5 years, on which you get about 12% per annum, and I’ll explain how.

The citizenship of UK costs about Rs 21 crores (GBP 2 million), of Malta costs over Rs 6 crores (EUR 700k+), but for Portugal it costs just about Rs 3 crores (EUR 350k)

You can invest this amount in real estate in Portugal, where since 2015, properties have appreciated by 8-10% annually, while giving 4-7% rental yields, thus giving 12% annual returns.

A tech company founder from Bangalore invested about Rs 4.5 crores (EUR 500k) in a Lisbon apartment five years ago - the property appreciated by 47%, generated rental income, AND he used Portugal as his European headquarters, expanding his business across the EU.

And here’s a sweetener… Portugal follows the “Non-Habitual Resident” tax program - you pay just 20% flat tax rate on professional income and potentially zero tax on foreign-source income for 10 years.

What’s the Cost of Living for a Nuclear Family in Toronto? 

How much money would you need if you want to move to Toronto with your family — that is, spouse and a young child — and lead a decent life?

-	Rentals will cost you about Rs 2.5 lakhs monthly (CAD 3500 – 4000), for a 2-bedroom apartment in a decent neighborhood like North York, Etobicoke, or Mississauga.

-	Groceries would add up to another Rs 75k (CAD 1250).

-	Transportation — whether it’s public transport (TTC) or a personal car lease plus insurance — would cost another Rs 50k (CAD 750).

-	Childcare can easily cost Rs 1 lakh (CAD 1500–2000) per month, if both parents are working.

-	Eating out, entertainment and lifestyle expenses: keep aside about Rs 1 lakh (CAD 1750).

-	Insurance, contingencies, medicals (even with OHIP in place): another Rs 50k (CAD 750).

Which means at least Rs 6 lakhs (roughly CAD 10,000) per month.

If your earning in Toronto is going to be less than CAD 120,000 post tax annually, you may be better off staying in India and earning Rs 2.5 lakhs per month instead.

This means, try and get a pre-tax salary package of no less than CAD 150,000 per annum for a half decent life.

Now, people also live in Toronto for easily 30% lesser than the above figures, but that’s with really cutting corners and being harsh on your spends.

This is how I’m seeing a few people double their pay in their 30s…

It comes with some risk but the pay off is totally worth it.

The concept of a Mini Retirement is increasingly becoming popular…
 
Increasingly, a number of people in their 30s are frustrated that their jobs keep them so busy with such administrative and repetitive work that even if they want to learn new skills to stay relevant, there is absolutely no time with work meetings, travel to the office, family commitments and more…
 
And this is even more frustrating when people realize that their juniors are switching companies, taking bigger promotions, and their experience is rusting their ability to be hired elsewhere…
 
Which is why the concept of a mini retirement is picking up where people decide to take a break from work for around 12 months…
 
Which would mean building up a fund to last you a year of expenses, moving to a cheaper destination or a tier 2 city, and then spending the next six months on just learning new skills like AI, Blockchain, or in whatever domain you want to upskill in…

And then coming back to applying to newer roles in the latter half, giving yourself one year to upskill and restart your career…
 
Some people are also taking up part time freelancing gigs during this period which helps them stay in the zone of working about 10 hours a week, while keeping the remaining time free to learn.
 
Think it’s a low cost self taught MBA break because even MBA colleges are not being able to keep up with new skills in today’s time.
 
These breaks are also being called “Mini Retirements” on the resume instead of sabbaticals, which when asked about during an interview, gives you an opportunity to show how you are invested in learning even when your colleagues are just doing the old things.
 
Companies like Adobe, Linkedin and AirBnB also have extended leave programs that help retain talent and reduce burnout.
 
The stigma attached to it is definitely going away.

I want to tell you something that happened with me yesterday…

I was checking into a hotel in New York… and saw that the person checking us in at the property was of brown descent…

Generally, over a chat I appreciated his swift assistance with the process, and over the conversation asked him where he was from…

He stopped for a few seconds and said Gujarat…

I could tell from the way he spoke that he was from across the border in Pakistan… and chose to say Gujarat because its a safe word that gives the impression that one is from India while few people know that there is a city called Gujarat in Pakistan.

And I’ve seen this time and again not just in the US, but in Canada, UK, Europe… no matter where you go…

People from Pakistan seem so embarrassed of their country often times that they present themselves as Indians…

You’ll see this also in the fact that most of the Indian restaurants being run in the UK are being run by Pakistanis but they will call it an Indian Restaurant and not Pakistani.

So it’s not something they’ll say to people who are Indian…

It’s often clear that a lot of Pakistanis abroad in Western economies are embarrassed of not just how their government behaves but also how it is perceived globally.

I have absolutely no hate for civilians and wish the well to all, but I also want to take this as an opportunity to say that the Indian brand has helped a lot of people across the border actually find a livelihood in other countries, and they should be mindful of how they behave with our country.

My condolences to everyone from India who lost their lives in the war, and a reminder to the world…

That its always Jai Hind before anything else.

After Analogue Paneer… the next product you’ll see a lot of adulteration and fakes are in your coffee…

In the past 5 years, coffee prices have gone up from $1000 a tonne to $5000 a tonne.

It’s a 5X increase in 5 years, and a 3X in the past 3 years…

It’s all because the demand for coffee around the world has gone so up north, that people who never cared about it earlier are now into collecting coffees, and enjoying unique brews multiple times a day…

This is fuelled with constantly dropping yields…

Two if the largest suppliers in the world are Brazil and Vietnam, and they’re both seeing a poor crop season.

There is a high chance that these prices may remain unpredictable for another couple of years… so coffee companies in India and around the world are facing a very tough time with increasing costs, and pressure to increase price which they feel the market will not accept…

I predict that your Instant Coffee brands will soon change their composition to add a lot more chicory powder, which is the root of a plant, roasted and mixed into coffee blends…

As for the cafés you go to, if they are really into serving the best single origin coffees, their prices should go up by about 20%… so a Rs 300 cup may now cost closer to Rs 400

Also, currently, the instant coffee brands have 70% actual coffee and the balance is chicory, so remember to check the ingredients to see what you’re really drinking.

We’ve teamed up with the enviably well-travelled foodie influencer @ClerkenwellBoyEC1 to bring you his handpicked selection of in-the-know culinary spots and things to do around Edinburgh this season. Read on for the first instalment…⁠

Edinburgh in Season⁠ with @clerkenwellboyec1: Tipo📍

@tipoedinburgh, the latest from the acclaimed team behind Aizle, Noto and Lyla, brings a vibrant dining experience to Edinburgh’s New Town. Tipo offers a delightful mix of small and large plates, including their Instagram-famous house-made pasta, cured meats and signature soft serve, all meant for sharing. The menu celebrates local and artisan Scottish produce, complemented by wines from small family-owned wineries and expertly crafted classic cocktails. Named after the fine Italian ‘00’ flour used for pasta, this relaxed and welcoming restaurant has quickly become a favourite for foodies. Recognised by the Michelin Guide with a Bib Gourmand for its quality and value, Tipo is your go-to spot for a memorable and delicious dining experience in the heart of the city.⁠

Exploring the beautiful region of Vienne Condrieu with @viennecondrieutourisme and @valleedelagastronomie 🙏🏼🇫🇷❤️ 

Nestled between Isère and Rhône, the region of Vienne Condrieu is steeped in history with vineyards dating back thousands of years, hidden Roman walls, and a majestic cathedral by the Rhône River. The perfect place to visit for lovers of wine, jazz, history and food! 🏛️ 

Highlights from our visit included…  

🍽️ Lunch at 2 Michelin-starred La Pyramide restaurant by Patrick Henriroux ~ housed within La Pyramide Maison Henriroux hotel with stunning suites, a beautiful bar, outdoor terraces and gardens. We loved the lunch tasting menu with incredible wine pairings and the cheese trolley of dreams 🧀

🍷 Taste wines at a family-run vineyard on gravity-defying slopes - we loved visiting Domaine Christophe Pichon @maison_pichon in the stunning Côte-Rôtie area,where we tried all their signature wines 

☕ A tour of the old town where you can visit the ancient cathedral and beautiful rose gardens 

🎷 Experience an open-air jazz concert in an ancient amphitheatre 

🏨 Stay in a charming family run hotel such as @domaine_clairefontaine - where dinner is cooked by the legendary Michelin-starred chef @philippegirardon - showcasing local produce but with innovative touches. If you ask nicely he might even show you his incredible Chartreuse collection!  

Thank you to my wonderful hosts! @viennecondrieutourisme @alpesishere @auvergnerhonealpes.tourisme @valleedelagastronomie @explorefrance 

🙏🏼🇫🇷❤️

Exploring the wonderful town of Tournus @tournustourisme and @valleedelagastronomie ☀️🇫🇷🥖🧀🍇🍷❤️

The charming town of Tournus is on the Saone River in the Saone-et-Loire department of southern Burgundy. With a history dating back to The Romans, we loved exploring the vibrant town centre, with its colourful houses, narrow alleys, cute bakeries, wonderful cheese & chocolate shops, ceramics and artist studios, cafes and restaurants. 

The 10th century benedictine Abbey of Saint-Philibert de Tournus is a must visit! We also recommend a visit to Hôtel-Dieu - a hospital (now museum) built in the 17th century with a lovely garden.

Other highlights included…

🧀 Lunch @lerelaisdozenay -where the chef champions local producers including ceramics artists, cheese makers and regional wine makers. 

🍷 Dinner Cloître restaurant @hotel_spa_les7fontaines by chef @stephane_gregoire.69 - where traditional Burgundy dishes have been re-invented with a modern twist.

🏨 Overnight stay and lovely breakfast @hotel_spa_les7fontaines - loved our massive suite, overlooking the sunny courtyard and huge bathrooms with roll top bathtubs. Also just a stone's throw away from the local village shops and cafes too.

🥂 Wine tasting @lesvigneronsdemancey - an immersive and interactive experience, learning all about the soil, climate, scents and smells of the local wines and vineyards. 

🍽️ Lunch at 1 Michelin starred Les Terrasses restaurant by chef Jean-Michel Carrette @auxterrasses_jm_carrette - An absolutely delicious lunch here! The market menu changes daily, using seasonal ingredients from local farmers and followed by desserts in the beautiful garden terrace - full of herbs and flowers.

Thank you to my wonderful hosts! @tournustourisme @bourgognefranchecomte_tourisme @mybourgogne @valleedelagastronomie @explorefrance 🙏🏼🇫🇷❤️
